## 5. API Handler Anatomy (Backend)

Every authenticated API handler follows this shape, in this sequence. Example uses JS/TS-style pseudocode - adapt syntax to your stack:

```
export async function POST(request) {
  // 1. AUTHENTICATE
  const actor = await getVerifiedSession();
  if (!actor) {
    return Response.json({ error: "Unauthorized" }, { status: 401 });
  }

  // 2. AUTHORIZE
  if (!hasPermission(actor, "resources:create")) {
    return Response.json({ error: "Forbidden" }, { status: 403 });
  }

  // 3. PARSE INPUT
  const body = await request.json();
  const { title, email, categoryId } = body;

  // 4. VALIDATE
  if (!title || !title.trim()) {
    return Response.json({ error: "Title is required" }, { status: 400 });
  }
  if (!isValidEmail(email)) {
    return Response.json({ error: "Invalid email format" }, { status: 400 });
  }

  // 5. EXECUTE
  try {
    const record = await db.create("Resource", {
      title: title.trim(),
      email: email.toLowerCase().trim(),
      category: categoryId,
      createdBy: actor.id,
    });

    const populated = await loadRelations(record, ["category"]);

    // 6. SIDE EFFECTS (after successful save)
    void sendConfirmation(record.email, record.title);
    void broadcastEvent("resource:created", populated);
    void logActivity(actor.id, "resource:create", record.id);

    // 7. RESPOND
    return Response.json(populated, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    return handleDatabaseError(error);
  }
}
```

**This is the default handler shape for authenticated CRUD endpoints.** Variations: public endpoints skip steps 1-2, webhooks start with signature verification, file uploads have a different parse step. The internal sequence of remaining steps stays the same.

> **i18n note:** The examples above use hardcoded English strings for clarity. When your project uses internationalization (see `internationalization.md`), replace all user-facing strings with translation keys: `t("errors.unauthorized")` instead of `"Unauthorized"`.

