## 6. UI Component Anatomy (Frontend)

Every component follows this internal sequence. Example uses React/JSX - adapt to your framework's component model:

```
// 1. Props type definition (if typed language)
interface ResourceCardProps {
  resource: Resource;
  onEdit: (id: string) => void;
  onDelete: (id: string) => void;
  isLoading?: boolean;
}

// 2. Component declaration
export function ResourceCard({ resource, onEdit, onDelete, isLoading = false }: ResourceCardProps) {
  // 3. Hooks (all hooks at the top, in this sequence)
  //    a. Context hooks
  const { permissions } = usePermissions();
  //    b. State hooks
  const [isConfirmOpen, setIsConfirmOpen] = useState(false);
  //    c. Derived / computed values
  const canEdit = hasPermission(permissions, "resources:edit");
  const canDelete = hasPermission(permissions, "resources:delete");
  //    d. Effect hooks
  useEffect(() => {
    // effect logic
  }, [dependency]);

  // 4. Event handlers
  function handleEditClick() {
    onEdit(resource.id);
  }

  function handleDeleteConfirm() {
    onDelete(resource.id);
    setIsConfirmOpen(false);
  }

  // 5. Early returns (loading, error, empty states)
  if (isLoading) {
    return <ResourceCardSkeleton />;
  }

  // 6. Render
  return (
    <div>
      <h3>{resource.title}</h3>
      <p>{resource.description}</p>
      {canEdit && <button onClick={handleEditClick}>Edit</button>}
      {canDelete && <button onClick={() => setIsConfirmOpen(true)}>Delete</button>}
      {isConfirmOpen && (
        <ConfirmDialog
          description="Delete this record?"
          onConfirm={handleDeleteConfirm}
          onCancel={() => setIsConfirmOpen(false)}
        />
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**This is the default component shape.** `forwardRef` wrappers, compound components, and animation-library integrations may adapt the structure - but keep the same logical grouping (hooks at top, handlers in middle, render at bottom).

### Rules (adapt terminology to your framework)

- **Type definitions at the top** - before the component (props interface, input types, etc.)
- **All reactive primitives at the top** of the component body - never inside conditionals or loops
- **Handlers before output** - defined as named functions, not inline in templates/markup
- **Early returns for states** - loading, error, empty before the main output
- **No business logic in output/render** - extract to functions or composables
- **Inline functions in templates** only for trivial one-liners (e.g., `onClick={() => setOpen(true)}` in JSX, `@click="open = true"` in Vue)
- **Complex inline logic** gets extracted to a handler function

