## 8. Type / Interface Pattern

**The principle:** Use your language's type system to its fullest. Prefer narrow types over escape hatches. Prefer composition over inheritance for type shapes. (Adapt to your type system: TypeScript uses `interface`/`type`, Python uses `dataclass`/`TypedDict`, Go uses `struct`, Rust uses `struct`/`trait`, Kotlin uses `data class`, Swift uses `struct`/`protocol`.)

```
// TypeScript example - adapt to your language's type system

// Simple types: type alias
type RecordStatus = "active" | "inactive" | "suspended";
type RecordId = string;

// Object shapes: interface
interface Resource {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  email: string;
  category: Category;
  status: RecordStatus;
  isActive: boolean;
  createdAt: Date;
  updatedAt: Date;
}

// Function signatures: type
type GetResourceById = (id: string) => Promise<Resource | null>;

// API request/response: interface
interface CreateResourceRequest {
  title: string;
  email: string;
  categoryId: string;
}

interface CreateResourceResponse {
  resource: Resource;
}

// Props: interface (with optional props having defaults)
interface ResourceListProps {
  categoryId: string;
  status?: RecordStatus;
  limit?: number;
}
```

### Rules

- **Prefer structured type definitions over untyped dictionaries/maps** - define the shape explicitly
- **Use the most specific type possible** - unions, enums, and literal types over generic strings/numbers
- **Never use type escape hatches** (TS: `any`, Python: untyped `dict`, Go: `interface{}`) without a justification comment explaining why the type cannot be narrowed
- **Prefer narrow unknown types over broad escape hatches** (TS: `unknown` over `any`, Python: typed protocols over `Any`) - force type checking at usage
- **Avoid type casting/assertions** unless absolutely necessary (and justify with a comment)
- **Types live near usage** - in the same file if used only there, in a shared types file if used across modules

